 result in a very bad fit for linear   regression:\']','[\'Python has methods for finding a relationship between data-points and to draw a line of linear regression. We will show you how to use these methods instead of going through the mathematic formula.\', \'In the example below, the x-axis represents age, and the y-axis represents speed. We have registered the age and speed of 13 cars as they were passing a tollbooth. Let us see if the data we collected could be used in a linear regression:\', \'Create a function that uses the slope and intercept values to return a new value. This new value represents where on the y-axis the corresponding x value will be placed:\', \'It is important to know how the relationship between the values of the x-axis and the values of the y-axis is, if there are no relationship the linear regression can not be used to predict anything.\', \'Note: The result -0.76 shows that there is a relationship,   not perfect, but it indicates that we could use linear regression in future   predictions.\', \'The result: 0.013 indicates a very bad relationship, and tells us that this data set is not suitable for linear regression.\']','[\'\n  import matplotlib.pyplot as pltx = [5,7,8,7,2,17,2,9,4,11,12,9,6]y = \n  [99,86,87,88,111,86,103,87,94,78,77,85,86]plt.scatter(x, y)plt.show()\', \'\n  import matplotlib.pyplot as pltfrom scipy import stats\nx = [5,7,8,7,2,17,2,9,4,11,12,9,6]y = \n  [99,86,87,88,111,86,103,87,94,78,77,85,86]slope, intercept, r, \n  p, std_err = stats.linregress(x, y)def myfunc(x):xa0 \n  return slope * x + interceptmymodel = list(map(myfunc, x))\n  plt.scatter(x, y)plt.plot(x, mymodel)plt.show()\', \'\n  from scipy import statsx = \n  [5,7,8,7,2,17,2,9,4,11,12,9,6]y = \n  [99,86,87,88,111,86,103,87,94,78,77,85,86]slope, intercept, r, \n  p, std_err = stats.linregress(x, y)print(r)\n\', \'\n  from scipy import stats\nx = [5,7,8,7,2,17,2,9,4,11,12,9,6]y = \n  [99,86,87,88,111,86,103,87,94,78,77,85,86]slope, intercept, r, \n  p, std_err = stats.linregress(x, y)def myfunc(x):xa0 \n  return slope * x + interceptspeed = myfunc(10)\n  print(speed)\', \'\n  import matplotlib.pyplot as pltfrom scipy import stats\nx = [89,43,36,36,95,10,66,34,38,20,26,29,48,64,6,5,36,66,72,40]y = \n  [21,46,3,35,67,95,53,72,58,10,26,34,90,33,38,20,56,2,47,15]slope, \n  intercept, r, p, std_err = stats.linregress(x, y)def \n  myfunc(x):xa0 return slope * x + interceptmymodel = list(map(myfunc, \n  x))plt.scatter(x, y)plt.plot(x, mymodel)plt.show()\', \'\n  import numpyfrom scipy import statsx = \n  [89,43,36,36,95,10,66,34,38,20,26,29,48,64,6,5,36,66,72,40]y = \n  [21,46,3,35,67,95,53,72,58,10,26,34,90,33,38,20,56,2,47,15]slope, intercept, r, \n  p, std_err = stats.linregress(x, y)print(r)\n\']','[]','[]'),(115,'[\'Machine Learning - Polynomial Regression\']','[\'Polynomial Regression\', \'How Does it Work?\', \'R-Squared\', \'Predict Future Values\', \'Bad Fit?\']','[\'Example\', \'Result:\', \'Example\', \'Result:\', \'Example Explained\', \'Example\', \'Example\', \'Example\', \'Result:\', \'Example\']','[\'https://www.w3schools.com/python/python_ml_linear_regression.asp\', \'https://www.w3schools.com/python/python_ml_multiple_regression.asp\', \'https://www.w3schools.com/python/showpython.asp?filename=demo_ml_polynomial_scatterplot\', \'https://www.w3schools.com/python/showpython.asp?filename=demo_ml_polynomial_regr\', \'https://www.w3schools.com/python/numpy/default.asp\', \'https://www.w3schools.com/python/scipy_intro.asp\', \'https://www.w3schools.com/python/trypython.asp?filename=demo_ml_polynomial_r\', \'https://www.w3schools.com/python/showpython.asp?filename=demo_ml_polynomial_predict\', \'https://www.w3schools.com/python/showpython.asp?filename=demo_ml_polynomial_badfit\', \'https://www.w3schools.com/python/trypython.asp?filename=demo_ml_polynomial_badfit_r\', \'https://www.w3schools.com/python/python_ml_linear_regression.asp\', \'https://www.w3schools.com/python/python_ml_multiple_regression.asp\']','[\'